---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import AuthorBio from '../../components/AuthorBio.astro';
const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens to the CGT cost base when a joint owner of a Brisbane property dies?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under section 128-15 of the Income Tax Assessment Act 1997, the deceased's interest is taken to have been acquired by the beneficiary (or the surviving joint tenant) at the date of death. For property the deceased acquired after 19 September 1985, the cost base of their share resets to the market value at the date of death only in limited circumstances (mainly where the property was the deceased's main residence just before death and not being used to produce income). In most other cases, the beneficiary or surviving owner inherits the deceased's original cost base. The surviving owner's existing share keeps its original cost base regardless. This is the most commonly misunderstood part of inherited Brisbane property sales."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does it matter whether we owned the property as joint tenants or tenants in common?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, but probably less than people think for CGT. For joint tenants, the ATO treats the deceased's interest as passing to the surviving joint tenant in equal shares as if under a will. The cost base rules in section 128-15 apply the same way. For tenants in common, the deceased's share passes through their estate to whoever is named in the will (which may or may not be the surviving co-owner). The CGT cost base treatment of the deceased's share is identical: the beneficiary inherits the deceased's cost base, or in the limited main residence cases, a market value reset at the date of death. The practical difference is who ends up owning the half-share and what happens at settlement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "If the property was the deceased's main residence, can we sell it CGT-free in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Often yes, but the rules in section 118-195 are specific. If the deceased acquired the property after 19 September 1985 and it was their main residence just before death and not used to produce assessable income at that time, the beneficiary can generally claim a full main residence exemption on disposal provided the property is sold within 2 years of the date of death (the Commissioner has discretion to extend this in limited cases). If the surviving owner already held a share and was also using the property as their main residence, the exemption can apply to both halves. If the deceased had moved out and rented it out, the exemption is partial and the cost base mechanics become significantly more complex. A specialist accountant should run the actual numbers before any campaign."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What records should I gather before listing an inherited Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Six things. First, the original purchase contract and settlement statement showing what the deceased (and any co-owner) paid and when. Second, the death certificate. Third, a market valuation of the property at the date of death from a registered valuer (not a real estate appraisal). Fourth, records of capital improvements made during the deceased's ownership: extensions, kitchens, bathrooms, structural work. Fifth, if the property was ever rented out, the depreciation schedules and capital works deductions claimed. Sixth, the grant of probate or letters of administration if applicable. Bringing this to the first accountant meeting (before listing) is the single most useful thing an executor or surviving owner can do."
      }
    }
  ]
};
